The Three Steps to Become an NRA Instructor
If you are passionate about firearms and gun safety, becoming an NRA instructor can be a rewarding and fulfilling career choice. In order to become an NRA instructor, there are three important steps you need to follow:

Step 1: Take and pass the NRA Basics of Pistol Shooting course
The first step in becoming an NRA instructor is to take and pass the NRA Basics of Pistol Shooting course. This course is a must for anyone looking to become an NRA instructor, as it covers the fundamental principles of pistol shooting and gun safety. It is important to have a solid foundation in these basics before moving on to the next steps. They want you to experance what you will be teaching.

Step 2: Pass the shooting qualification and hands-on portion
Once you have completed the Basics of Pistol Shooting course, you will need to pass the shooting qualification and hands-on portion of the training. This portion of the training will test your skills and knowledge of pistol shooting and gun safety. It is important to practice and prepare for this part of the training in order to successfully pass and move on to the next step. The qualification for Level 4 requires the shooter to fire 20 shots from a standing position at a target 15 yards away. 16 of the 20 shots must be within a 6-inch group on an 8 inch circle.

Step 3: Take and pass the NRA instructor course
The final step in becoming an NRA instructor is to take and pass the NRA instructor course. This course will provide you with the necessary training and certification to become an NRA instructor. It will cover topics such as teaching techniques, classroom management, and range safety procedures. Once you have completed this course and passed the required exams wit a 90% or greater, you will officially become an NRA instructor.

By following these three steps, you can become an NRA instructor and help educate others on the importance of gun safety and responsible firearm ownership. Becoming an NRA instructor is a valuable and rewarding career choice for anyone passionate about firearms and gun safety.
